# Take That Look Off Your Face

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Jump to: navigation, search

"Take That Look Off Your Face"  
---

"**Take That Look Off Your Face** " is the title of a hit song by [musical
theatre](/wiki/Musical_theatre "Musical theatre") composer [Andrew Lloyd
Webber](/wiki/Andrew_Lloyd_Webber "Andrew Lloyd Webber"). Collaborating with
lyricist [Don Black](/wiki/Don_Black_\(lyricist\) "Don Black \(lyricist\)"),
it was written for the song cycle show _[Tell Me on a
Sunday](/wiki/Tell_Me_on_a_Sunday "Tell Me on a Sunday")_ in 1978. It was sung
and released by [Marti Webb](/wiki/Marti_Webb "Marti Webb") in 1980, and
became a No.3 hit in the UK charts. The song was also popular in Ireland, and
spent six weeks at number one. Later, _Tell Me on a Sunday_ was combined with
another Lloyd Webber work,
_[Variations](/wiki/Variations_\(Andrew_Lloyd_Webber_album\) "Variations
\(Andrew Lloyd Webber album\)")_ , to form an entire new show, _[Song and
Dance](/wiki/Song_and_Dance "Song and Dance")_.

The song is about a woman being told of her boyfriend's infidelity. The woman
denies this initially, before rebuking her newsbearer (a girlfriend) with the
revelation that she "knew before" and had done for some time. She also spends
much of the song criticising her friend for rushing to break the "bad news" to
her.

Despite having been written during the creative process for _Tell Me on a
Sunday_ , the song wasn't recorded during the album's principal sessions.
Black reminded Lloyd Webber that they had missed a track, then entitled "You
Must Be Mistaken". [John Mole](/wiki/John_Mole_\(musician\) "John Mole
\(musician\)"), the [bass guitar](/wiki/Bass_guitar "Bass guitar") player,
improvised a part reminiscent of the arrangement style of [Phil
Spector](/wiki/Phil_Spector "Phil Spector"), inspiring the rest of the
orchestration. The track was recorded in one take, apart from a [double
tracking](/wiki/Double_tracking "Double tracking") of the orchestra.

A briefer 3:02 edit of the song is included on the album, however, a longer
3:29 version remixed with greater [dynamic range
compression](/wiki/Dynamic_range_compression "Dynamic range
compression")[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed
"Wikipedia:Citation needed")_] was released as the
[single](/wiki/Single_\(music\) "Single \(music\)").

## Track
listing[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Take_That_Look_Off_Your_Face&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Track listing")]

  * Side A: "Take That Look Off Your Face"
  * Side B: "Sheldon Bloom"

##
Revisions[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Take_That_Look_Off_Your_Face&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Revisions")]

The lyrics were substantially rewritten by [Richard Maltby,
Jr](/wiki/Richard_Maltby,_Jr. "Richard Maltby, Jr.") for the original Broadway
production of _Song and Dance_. The British productions of the show have
always used the lyrics written by Black.

Black himself amended the line, "He's doing some deal up in Baltimore now"
after realising that Baltimore is south of New York. In subsequent versions,
the song's protagonist is said to be "down" in Baltimore.

For the 2003 production of _Tell Me on a Sunday_ , the storyline instead
placed the action in England prior to an emigration to New York, requiring
some further revision of the lyrics to reference London instead.
